Although, this is not mentioned in the Stream documentation nor in the [distinct documentation][1]. I believe this is considered implied, as the [`equals` documentation][2] amply covers the obligation in honoring the general hashcode contract when overriding the `equals` method.

&gt; Note that it is generally necessary to override the hashCode method whenever this method is overridden, so as to maintain the general contract for the hashCode method, which states that equal objects must have equal hash codes.

In fact, your snippet produces the desired output once the `hashCode()` method has been overridden.

```
